history.content:
I can't speak to CS186, but as someone who's taken EE16A and am currently taking CS170 I'd say it's very doable if you enjoyed CS70/have a good study group.  I also took math 54 before EE16A and found the linalg part of EE16A to be super easy and the circuits part to be pretty hard, so I'd highly recommend staying on top of your discussions and homeworks.  CS170 is fairly difficult in terms of problems/sheer work, but with a solid homework group you'll be fine.

Goodluck!

CS186 is not very time consuming. You are assigned 4 projects that are meant to take around 15 hours (although could be much quicker or longer depending on the person, I finished the first two projects in ~10 hours each and I'm no where near a CS all-star). On a weekly basis there isn't really much work, just go to lecture, discussion, and do a homework assignment every couple weeks (graded on completion, google form).

I can't speak to CS186, but as someone who's taken EE16A and am currently taking CS170 I'd say it's very doable if you enjoyed CS70/have a good study group.  I also took math 54 before EE16A and found the linalg part of EE16A to be super easy and the circuits part to be pretty hard, so I'd highly recommend staying on top of your discussions and homeworks.  CS170 is fairly difficult in terms of problems/sheer work, but with a solid homework group you'll be fine.

Goodluck!

Anyone have any experiences or thoughts on this Fall 2017 schedule: CS 170, CS 186, EE 16A, and CS research (2 units).

Note: I've taken Math 54, but want to re-learn a lot of the stuff because I don't feel like I learned much from the class.

Thank you.
